│ bitwidth of abs intrinsic, it second argument must be set false". The problem is that this transformation is unsafe when there's a truncation after the abs. Actually, looking at the     │
│ original code again: the abs is on i64 values, then truncated to i32. If we reduce the bitwidth of abs from i64 to i32, we're effectively doing truncation before abs, which changes      │
│ semantics.                                                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                           │
│ The fix should be: when we have `trunc(abs(x))`, we can't reduce the bitwidth of abs because `trunc(abs(x)) != abs(trunc(x))` in general. The SLP vectorizer should not reduce bitwidth   │
│ for abs when its result is truncated.                                                                                                                                                     │
